ing. In the Castle Doctrine, I never felt rewarded at any point, even after robbing a high-valued house successfully. Because I could barely make myself a decent defense (and seeing how many griefers there are in the game, it barely counts unless you are REALLY rich)How to sum-up if you didn't felt like reading all of this ? Frustrating and not rewarding, boring, expensive for such a minimalistic game, and the game doesn't match up to the concept. Definitely, I couldn't recommend it to anyone. Watching videos of it and looking at the concept is just filling your head with illusions, seriously."
,Not Recommended,249570,8941744,"Posted: 1 February, 2014",all,Thraka,"I have played this game for 21 hours so far... I give it a 5/10. Please read on to find out why!In the beginning...At first, the game starts out very cool. You're new to everything. There are a lot of tiles to play with. The best way to learn how to make something, is to venture into someone else's house and die. ""Clever..."" you think to yourself, ""I'll use that trap!""After awhile, you learn how things work, so you set off to create your own house. With $2000 starting cash, you don't have a lot to work with. You don't want to spend too much making your house, because the left over money will be what people see, and they won't bother to take the time to try and beat your security for a measly $250-$500.Really, you only have $600-$800 to spend to make sure you attract burglars. Not much in fact. A guard dog costs you around $300. Electrical stuff is cheaper though.To attack, or not to attack...If you decide to venture out and attack others, you can buy tools to help you. The tools let you bypass specific types of security measures. Run into a dog? Use one of your sleep-laden-dog treats. Be careful though, you only have as many as you purchased. And other things like that. Every trap component has a counter of some sort.If you attack someone's house, and decide that their design is just something you won't beat, and you will die trying, you can leave through the front door. However, if you do so, you forfeit all items you purchased to help you break in successfully. If you happen to make it all the way to their safe, you get money, but that is money minus what you spent on tools to make it there. Generally, one way or another, attacking another player, who understands how the game works (which everyone does sooner or later) will end up costing you money because it is hard to break into a decent house without tools.If you happen to become successful a few times, and have built yourself a little stash of money, or you're fortunate enough to have some people attack you and die trying, you will then have enough money to start building some really cool traps. The side-effect of building your own nice house though, you stop attacking others. You won't be looking to die turning some corner 10 seconds into a robbery and then have to start over completely.When you're poor at the start, spend $1000 for tools, and attack a house with $3000. You will come away with more than you started, though it may take you 20 tries to do so. A  bit tedious. When you're rich, or you've built your house, never attack anyone again.ConclusionThis game really has a lot of cool concepts.Pros1. Permadeath is really neat because it gives you a good risk-reward factor.2. The traps and tiles you can place add a lot of variety and allow you to create some really cool things.3. All houses are user-created4. You get to solve puzzles, one section at a time (through fog-of-war, you only see what your character can see)5. The more successful you are, the more you can build.Cons1. Expect to lose, lose, lose, and lose. There really is no way to win. You will die eventually, no way around it, unless you get so much money that you can build an entire fortress within your walls. But then at that point, there is no reason to even play the game any more. You don't want to risk venturing out and losing everything. Your money keeps growing because people want to get a piece of it.2. You cannot build, what you want, how you want, until you have enough money to do so.3. The risk of getting money at the start is very high.4. All houses are user-created. This is generally a good thing. Player made content is fun. However, because of the high risk-reward of the core design of the game, you will see the same cheap and easily duplicated puzzles that without spending lots of money on tools to destroy the house itself, you can never beat.5. There are some bad UI design flaws that hurt you. Want to review how someone attacked your house? You can do so, but while you are reviewing, others may attack you. If you have a lot of money in your house, it may be impossible for you to get in it to fix what others have broken, or even change the design. You cannot even look at your house while it is being broken into. I constantly have the problem of attack after attack without being able to get in my house and fix things.6. No way to save/load your design. You can use an online builder to create and save a design, but you will be reconstructing it in the game piece-by-piece, no zooming in or out to get the big picture.Final ThoughtsBut this game executes these great concepts poorly. It may be that that all of these concepts are actually executed well by this game, but all of these concepts put together just do not work well.The game gives you a great feeling at the start, it's a lot of fun to explore it all. But once you see how it all works, it's like discovering who the Wizard of Oz really is. You'll be handicapped at the start to try and make money so that you can design a cool intricate puzzle that in all reality, only you could ever solve on the first try.So what is the point? Where is all the fun? It's not here. Once more people get tired of the game, and I honestly think they will, the game will fade. It's been stated by the creator it will never, ever, again be on sale. At a cheaper price than it is, say 75% off, lots of players could be introduced to it that would get a kick out of it for awhile, and give the die-hard-masochist fan base some fresh meat to play with, but without it.....dead game"
