76561198098643084,Recommended,249570,8992294,"Posted: 5 February, 2014",all,CriticalMammal,"The concept and design of this game often cross into brilliant territory. I haven't had a game make me feel so clever in a while. I spent the first few hours of the game meticulously setting up my maze of traps that involved making some cats flip some switches that activate some electric floor panels behind any potential intruder. I found myself engrossed with the idea of trying to create something to outsmart another player. It worked... and worked again... yes I thought, this is marvelous.Then someone cut down a wooden wall that led to my family, shot down my wife and brutally clubbed my children to death. Oh my. I wrote down his name with some idea of revenge planted in my head. Then I thought about it and realized this game was leading me down a dark path. I started working on my house again...This isn't to say that I don't think the game has some issues with balance and some other areas. I find that you want to often save a fair amount of money on a new life to make yourself a nice juicy target for some burglar. This is odd I thought to myself... I want people to break into my house. Without them I'll have no income... unless I go out and rob other people. I tried to rob other people but I soon found that other people's deathtraps rely heavily on presenting you with so many paths you're bound to fail at some point or another. Without tools you'll have no way to escape from a deadly situation, but I spent most of my money on my house... and tools are expensive.Essentially I found that the game presents you with a paradox of sorts. While it wants you to realize that being a robber or killing people in your house isn't a good thing, it doesn't really give you any other option. There is no honest living in this game, you either steal lives in self-defense or you go out and rob other people's houses.Still though, through all of this I still would recommend this game. The thrill of trying to outwit other players is too satisfying of an experience. I'm not sure I've ever really played anything quite like it. It's tense and everything feels weighty. It's really something how this game creates such a cynical atmosphere."
