76561198037769394,Not Recommended,249570,10058526,"Posted: 8 May, 2014",all,BDTA,"I'd like to start by saying I heard about this game via YouTube and the series i watched was incredible enjoyable. I decided to give the game a shot since it looked at the very least decent. I picked it up while it was on sale and using some tips from the series I watched and reddit I made a simple house with a commitment trap and a electric floor lock out type trap as well as gave my wife a shot gun. I went out and got lucky with a few houses that had been broken into but not robbed... this is where I noticed one of the first major problems, if your wife is alive and you have a decent amount of money her death is enough for some people since they'll get half and any damage they have done to your house will remain (whereas if they die it gets fixed). Death of the wife seems to be higher up on some peoples lists if they can afford a gun, (guns have a range of 2 spaces whereas your wife's shot gun has a range of 1) and as such people will ""dance"" near the entrance or search for your family to get them to make their way to the door. I've also noticed that people will occasionally just enter someone's house to mess it up and kill a family member, probably in revenge for stealing their money. So, after I had some decent cash and upgraded my home significatly I let it sit for a while to see how many people I'd kill, and what I'd get with my house. for the most part I'd have people entering the house, taking 2~5 steps then backing out once they saw a commitment trap or a dog, or even just a door... the only time I'd see someone stay longer is if they had a full bag of tools that usually cost more than my savings, and even then most people wouldn't stay in very long and even would back out before they robbed my house. When someone finally successfully robbed my house they also killed my wife, leaving me with a broken home and absolutely no money. At this point it was virtually impossible for me to ""recover"" as most houses that I would go to rob had only a few dollars in them and were too risky, I ended up just starting over, which leads me to another major flaw... the prices of just about everything. All robbery tools cost hundreds of dollars, most effective house defense stratagies cost thousands in total, and the most effective are also incredibly cheap feeling as they are mostly combo locks after a commitment trap and the wrong combo permenantly locks you in the house while locking off the safe forever causing you to have to suicide. I feel if you were given some materials to build and rob with at the beginning of a ""fresh start"" and you kept your materials after surviving a hosue 2000 wouldn't be a bad starting point but as it stands it's barely enough to protect anything. Also normal doors can't be locked... which is just silly to me, the game lets you buy an electric locking thick metal door for a few hundred dollars, but we can't find a simple lock for a door. the purpose a lock on a normal door could hold would be to waste a ""movement turn"" breaking the lock(no tools, just slamming into it with your shoulder or something) and causing everything/everyone within a certain radius to notice someone's in the house. It could also act as a way to block off your family (they'd have keys) so that they don't need a very very obvious escape route, as mentioned int he video they need an escape route that's 100% obsticle free (aside from dogs).Originally there was a ""salary"" that your character and your wife(if your wife died it was just your salary) would earn while you where away from the game (more the more time you where not playing) to suppliment stealing and house defense, it also made more sense that you where out of the house when you where getting robbed that way. But they took it out I assume to controll the money flow of the game and as a balancing attempt... but I think it unbalanced the game more than it helped and it made it so that there is truely no recovery from having your wife killed and your house robbed (barring getting lucky as hell while robbing someone with more than $50 and a broken home...Some commonly used traps/deturants that can be considered ""cheap tactics"" include:""leaps of faith"" where they have an open trap door that you're supposed to assume a cat/dog will activate and close as you step onto it""Commitment traps"" such as an electric grill flooring or an electric door that locks/turns on as you pass it so there is no turning back and it's pretty much get the money or die trying scenario.""death traps"" there are many of these that are usually hidden behind commitment traps and literally force you to die, a simple one is to hide a cat around a corner behind some glass and cover the floor in grills so it looks like a simple commitment trap, but once they turn the corner they scare the cat and it hits a switch frying the person on the plates, another variant is the same thing but uses a small dog to run towards you.""Dog traps"" basically dogs behind doors that lead to no where, again when paired with a commitment trap this can be deadly...So many ways to trap people in this game, some are super easy to make, some are very expensive and most are not effective by them selves and require at least a few to protect your money.Overall this game has a great concept and a decent execution, but it has some major flaws and some major balancing issues.As it stands I would not reccomend this game. I think it needs to be improved in many ways before I'd say give it a shot, especially for the $16 asked for it, if it was maybe $5  I'd say give it a shot and if you don't like it... hell at least it'd only be $5 spent."
