,Not Recommended,249570,8921824,"Posted: 31 January, 2014",all,Kana,"In a nutshell, a brilliant idea, but execution so awful it's obvious it's the developer's first attempt at making any manner of a game, with possibly little to no experience in the field of game development even in general.For instance, it's entirely possible you spend a good 30-40 minutes wiring up a house to your liking for the very first time, and then you decide to test it out, because the game requires you to.So, you of course test your traps, let's say the electrified floortrap to see what it does, whether it's some sort of humorous zapping animation or something else. What this actually does, is instantly kills you for good, and permanently deletes any of your previous effort on the house.The game has no way of informing you about any of this, and the only way to find out is experimentation. There is no manual, there isn't even a wiki.There are other glaring issues, such as the obvious design of going with a multiple choice lottery where only one of a 5 dozen switches opens the vault, and all the other are lethal. You obviously know which one to press, the chances of an invading player knowing this are neglibly small. Protecting the family is a pointless matter by design, as there are no reasonable ways to protect them whatsoever. Why? They require an entirely trapless (and doorless) way out of your house. There are 3 familymembers. There are no turrets or any sort of traps like that, and the dogs are a joke to dispose of.Such a shame; the idea is worth developing for, but the execution is lacking on all grounds. Please do not waste your money or time with this.Also, i'll just leave 2 figures out here:Sale price: 14,99€Size on HD : 2,2mbThis should tell you how much effort has gone to this game at large, as opposed to how much is being asked for the game.I'd personally rate a similar game, ""The pay-to-win quest for mediocre loot"" above this, and it's obvious how i feel for that one."
