76561197983412937,Recommended,249570,9739155,"Posted: 5 April, 2014",all,PANIC,"This game -- It is a brilliant idea and extremely addicting. It is not for everyone, so please read the following before you decide to buy the game.Firstly I want to state that all the critics giving this game a bad review should not be allowed to even rate a game like The Castle Doctrine. I mean this with no hate but if your job is to quickly play a game and write a report about it, day in day out, then you will NOT be able to appreciate a game that involves thinking/learning such as this.Short summery: You are given a house with some money and you build traps to keep other players out. Afterwards you have the choice of either logging off and waiting for people to die(get money) or break into your vault, or invading someone elses house. Once someone breaks into your house you can actually watch footage of how they do so. The amount of people in the game is very active. Once I build my house, people normally bite within minutes.If you have played Minecraft and enjoy the 'engineering' aspect of the game where you build and wire items together, you will enjoy this game. At first the amount of items may seem overwhelming but the learning curve is small. Once you have given the game a chance, and come to appreciate that every single house you enter is the fabrication of someone elses individual imagination, you will LOVE the game. The amount of traps and mazes that people create is AMAZING. It makes no difference how long you have played, you will always be a student in this game. You cannot ever master this game because there will likely be someone that will figure your design out -- that's the point of the game!The game lacks a tutorial for good reason -- this game is for people that like to think/innovate. If you enjoy games that are linear, hand things out, or have safety nets, then you will not enjoy this game. The punishment of failure is very large and you will die a lot at first, however you are given all the tools to test your designs at will. If you dare to copy someone elses design, expect people to have already seen it(you better add a new spin onto it).Recommendations: Play around with all the different types of items, or watch a quick youtube video on how they work. Then go into other peoples houses to explore, and die, and die, and die, and die, and die again. You lose nothing as a newbie so check out how some other people are creating houses. Then create a simple house and watch how someone robs you. If you fail, recreate it and improve on the design -- simple as that.Personal tactic: I fill up my backpack with saws in order to try and rob someone as a complete newbie. I break into a house that is worth more than the starting amount of money and try to saw my way through as much as possible, minding traps. If I reach a vault then I will likely double my cash, and then create a house from scratch with more money then I originally had. If I die, I respawn and repeat the above until I crack someone's house. Along the way I see cool looking traps and try to replicate them. ONCE I build a house, I never rob anyone. I logout and wait for people to die to my traps, and then build more and more."
